Timing Accuracy Analysis:

1. 1kHz (Period = 1ms):
- Using 1:8 prescaler
- PR2 = 19999
- Resolution = 0.2μs
- Theoretical error < 0.02%

2. 10kHz (Period = 100μs):
- Using 1:8 prescaler
- PR2 = 1999
- Resolution = 0.2μs
- Theoretical error < 0.2%

3. 100kHz (Period = 10μs):
- Using 1:1 prescaler
- PR2 = 199
- Resolution = 0.025μs
- Theoretical error < 0.25%

Factors affecting accuracy:
1. Crystal tolerance (typically 50-100ppm)
2. Temperature variations
3. ISR execution time variations
4. Interrupt latency

To improve accuracy:
1. Use hardware output compare module instead of GPIO toggling
2. Compensate for ISR execution time
3. Use higher priority for Timer2 interrupt
4. Consider temperature compensation for critical applications

Here's a complete RTC implementation with millisecond precision:

```
c typedef struct {
  uint16_t milliseconds; // 0-999
  uint8_t seconds;       // 0-59
  uint8_t minutes;       // 0-59
  uint8_t hours;         // 0-23
  uint32_t totalSeconds; // For long-term tracking
} RTC_Time;

volatile RTC_Time currentTime = {0};
volatile uint16_t msCounter = 0;

// Configure Timer1 for precise timing
void configureRTC(void) {
  // Use Timer1 with 32.768kHz crystal
  T1CON = 0x0002; // External 32.768kHz source, 1:1 prescale
  PR1 = 32;       // 32 ticks = 0.977ms (close to 1ms)

  _T1IF = 0;
  _T1IE = 1;
  _T1IP = 7; // Highest priority for accuracy

  T1CONbits.TON = 1;
}

// Timer1 ISR - Called approximately every 1ms
void __attribute__((interrupt, auto_psv)) _T1Interrupt(void) {
  static uint16_t correctionCounter = 0;
  _T1IF = 0;

  // Increment milliseconds
  currentTime.milliseconds++;
  msCounter++;

  // Apply correction every second
  // 32.768kHz/32 = 1024 interrupts per second
  // Need to skip 24 increments to get exactly 1000ms
  if (msCounter >= 1024) {
    msCounter = 0;
    correctionCounter++;

    // Time rollover management
    currentTime.milliseconds = 0;
    currentTime.seconds++;
    currentTime.totalSeconds++;

    if (currentTime.seconds >= 60) {
      currentTime.seconds = 0;
      currentTime.minutes++;

      if (currentTime.minutes >= 60) {
        currentTime.minutes = 0;
        currentTime.hours++;

        if (currentTime.hours >= 24) {
          currentTime.hours = 0;
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

// Function to set current time
void setTime(uint8_t hours, uint8_t minutes, uint8_t seconds) {
  T1CONbits.TON = 0; // Stop timer during update

  currentTime.hours = hours;
  currentTime.minutes = minutes;
  currentTime.seconds = seconds;
  currentTime.milliseconds = 0;
  currentTime.totalSeconds =
      (uint32_t)hours * 3600 + (uint32_t)minutes * 60 + seconds;

  msCounter = 0;

  T1CONbits.TON = 1; // Restart timer
}
```

